<subSubSection box="[199,1170,1556,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1232,1761]" box="[199,1170,1556,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1556,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name refers to the tumid upper part of the face in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1232,1761]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1592,1617]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is similar to several species all predominantly black with the apical area of the forewing paler and with a relatively slender body (see under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[828,940,1629,1652]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis box="[828,842,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[855,940,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[1025,1130,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis box="[1025,1130,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1183,1273,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ereba">
<emphasis box="[1183,1273,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. ereba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a similar aedeagal shaft with well developed dorsal apodeme and shaft curved first posteriorly and then anteriorly. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has spicules on lateral margins of aedeagal shaft that are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[1054,1163,1700,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis box="[1054,1163,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the latter has both clypeus and clypellus tumid which is not the case in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[740,871,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis box="[740,871,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
